Munich, 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A mental institution where young people meet today.
A tomb chapel, now being dug for the subway tunnel.
Small gardeners tend the land once owned by farmers.
The oldest official map of Munich reveals exciting stories.
It's annoying when maps aren't up to date.
Anyone who's ever had to get upset because the traffic light showed a green meadow instead of a bypass road knows that.
The historical maps of the digital Bavarian atlas, a service provided by the Bavarian State Government's Geoportal, are far from up-to-date - but are therefore very informative.
Especially when you compare it to current online maps.
It will then show how cities and municipalities in the Munich Mercury distribution area have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavarian atlas is a patchwork of patches that are not immediately recognizable as such.
The large overview map incorporates more detailed maps of cities and municipalities, known as Urpositionblätter.
These were created between 1810 and 1864 according to the Bavarian Survey Administration and originate from the first survey of Bavaria.
Her client is Napoleon.
The French commander occupied Bavaria from the spring of 1800 during the War of the Second Coalition with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographic survey of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Although the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was the present-day neighbours who created the idea of a land-wide Bavarian map.
Elector Max IV Joseph pushed the project forward, founding the "Topographical Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Survey Administration.
The original position sheet for Munich dates from 1856 and can be found on the Internet site of the Bavarian State Library.
The comparison between then and now is most striking in the case of the capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example is Untersendling, which appears relatively isolated on the 1856 map.
Sendling was incorporated 21 years after the map was drawn up, in 1877, as a borough of Munich.
Today, the underworld is in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendlings are concentrated around 1856 along the present-day Plinganserstraße, which was named after Georg Sebastian Plinganser in 1878, a leader of the uprising of Bavarian peasants against Austria in 1705.
Where the West Park is today, you see nothing but fields - at first glance: when zooming in, a smaller map appears with dozens of lines and numbers: hand-numbered plots from the so-called "original record" from which the property tax was derived.
Small plots are no longer occupied by farmers - but by small gardeners from the "Land in Sun".
A large green area is to the north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, the site of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was actually a meadow in the 19th century - not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the Urpositionsblatt, in the area of today's Au-Haidhausen district, you can read not only the street name "am Gasteig" or the hill "Auf den Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstrasse, people with delusions were once locked up.
It was there that the Munich County Lunatic Asylum "On the Auer Lüften" was founded in 1858/59.
From 1872 onwards, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - the psychiatrist who is brought in in connection with the death of King Ludwig II.
"He was progressive for his time, for example, ending the inquisition of the so-called lunatics.
He also forbade the staff to use violence against the inmates", says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, who worked on an exhibition for the institution.
Initially, 280 patients were accommodated, but this was later increased to 500.
At some point, even this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the district icehouse in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum Munich-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany, has been located there.
On the grounds of the former Auer institution, young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training facilities.
To the west is the football field of TSV München Ost, to the east are residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's home "Casa Don Bosco" was built - in architectural style of the original building of the asylum for the insane, which was destroyed in World War II in bomb attacks.
The Marienplatz was listed as the "Mainplatz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstrasse was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change to the heart of Munich.
Allied bombs tore many holes in the city center in December 1944.
A large one remained until today - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small commercial buildings and a medieval graveyard chapel once stood at the Marienhof, where the preliminary work and the groundbreaking for the second S-Bahn main line are currently taking place.
The slider compares the old Munich map with today's aerial view and fills in the hole at Marienhof.
A civil rights group has issued a travel advisory for Missouri .
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri due to the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, urges African American travelers, visitors and Missourians to exercise extreme caution and caution when traveling through the state as a number of questionable, race-based incidents have recently occurred throughout the state and are noted here", the group's statement said.
A recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state's law enforcement agencies disproportionately targeting minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"You have civil rights violations that happen to people.
They are stopped because of their color, they are beaten or killed", Missouri NAACP president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We're hearing complaints at a frequency we've never heard before".
It is the first such warning the organization has issued to a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist abuse against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while traveling through the state and being taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The Council also points to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's office showing that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped in the state than white drivers.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and employees about what could happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People have to be prepared whether it's bringing bail money or letting relatives know they're traveling through the state".
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest numbers from the FBI's Hate Crime Reporting Program, which ranks the state 16th in the nation in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a business for housing or employment discrimination.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after the states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently, interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
