Nothing is sacred anymore?
Now the Trump White House is taking over the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
The Americans value this as much as any other - hence the carefully staged overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with CNN's Jim Acosta about the president's proposals to drastically curb legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller didn't attack the statue itself.
A bunch of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he did.
But he attacked its meaning, and especially the meaning attributed to it, when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
When Miller Acosta scolded, "I don't want to go into a whole thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you're referring to was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller is factually correct, but as he put it, it's not really about history.
It is about the contemporary response to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only one in which a state invites not just any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your tired, your poor, / your oppressed masses who yearn to breathe freely, / the miserable waste of your rich shores".
There has never been a better time to see the "miserable waste" on our screens.
Miller wasn't engaged in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's U.S.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural debate: it's actually a conflict over the meaning of America.
Lazarus and her friends, who were committed to putting their words on the ground after her death, knew very well that they were doing a highly political thing.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classic pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: In her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has a voice.
And she gives herself a whole other name: Mother of the Exile.
The link between the poem and the picture is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right wing people have long wanted to change that.
The big-mouthed Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist for Trump's coming, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative bringing the American flame into the night-bound world: "Lady Liberty is going forward.
She's supposed to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not to light the way to the United States".
It's quite unusual that Limbaugh came across something here.
The significance of the statue is entirely a matter of perception.
Lazarus' great act of imagination was to see her as she was seen by the exhausted, miserable, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after long and often terrible journeys.
It's really about seeing the world from the perspective of people who are looking for refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Her statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that's not the perspective that Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch should not light the way, but ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
