Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand the heat from voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't take long for the newspapers to beat him up for everything from his domestic policies to his political principles.
He was a bit of a critic, I'm sure.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we will be led like sheep to the slaughter".
Which brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to work on being more like Washington.
Hogan's staff has blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and online commentary was full of a backlash with "So, what?"
"It's just Facebook", many people said.
But it's important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in a vastly overwhelmingly democratic state that is amazingly popular.
He has the second-highest approval rating of the 50 governors in the nation.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown firmness in the leadership of his country and strict adherence to principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as a primary means of connecting with his constituents and debuting his hairless head after chemotherapy on his page.
So blocking people who come to the governor's side - which is a public forum that's called official and staffed by people who are paid with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people whipping up the whip online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a minister, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not profane.
The minister quoted the Bible in his letter and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., was not hateful, but she was asking about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other current news", she wrote in the comments section of The Post news program.
"I also do not like this idea, when a number of people have a say on the same issue, then they are dismissed by some as a so-called collective effort and not recognized as a large group of concerned citizens".
What the governor's staff called a "concentrated spam attack" others would probably call "spam".
The Facebook era makes it easy to cut a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than in the old days, when you would have done the same thing, sending employees to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or arrest and silence protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening digitally right now.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for abusing Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones in this matter came last week in Virginia.
The chairwoman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable port had an effect similar to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers responded to his leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people who used pseudonyms like "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius", and "Portius" all wrote letters to newspapers denigrating Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected from the George Washington Project's online papers.
But he didn't shut them up.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are the foundation of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
