Less lung cancer deaths from secondhand smoke
In the past two decades, fewer people have died from lung cancer due to secondhand smoke.
This is the conclusion reached by scientists at the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) in a study.
"We estimate that 167 lung cancer deaths a year are due to secondhand smoke", said study leader Heiko Becher.
He used his own study on the subject from 1994 as a comparison.
At that time, there were still 400 lung cancer deaths per year in Germany due to secondhand smoke.
The new study is published in the International Journal of Public Health.
