Poverty and Death in the Indonesian Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai Regency in Indonesia's troubled province of Papua, the housewife usually places a sweet potato - locally called "nota" - directly in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and swallowed with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the mud floor - she has no furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing clothes with cloudy water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: Most villagers are unemployed, many drink heavily, and there are soldiers here.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m"., she says.
It is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was incorporated in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were asked to vote by publicly raising their hands before the occupying forces.
An existing movement for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which controls the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea comprising the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is boring, and the journey includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and then a five-hour morning drive by rental car.
There is no public transport.
The city of about 19,000 is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated tin roofs that have been rusted to various yellowish-brown hues.
Very few Indonesians have made the journey here, let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, the Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, pointing to her vibrant, hand-woven turban, dark shirt, and light skirt.
"We used to have leaves on our bodies".
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, where 28 percent of the population lives below the poverty line and has some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold country.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, is just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated $78 billion.
But these riches are a source of misery for Papua, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 investigation in The New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden geese and they are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua's tribal highlands in the 1970s were classified as genocide by the Asian Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
"We will lose everything", says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities from the previous year, including unlawful executions and torture - rape and electrocution are especially popular, according to another report - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week", says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but the demographic trend is changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Locals are struggling to keep up.
"The migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at a cheaper price than the local Papuan market", explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai resident who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura to work.
"It cost the local Papuans - the Mama-Mama [women] of Papua - their market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to address inequality and human rights abuses in Papua.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua's 29 districts - including Paniai - on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored", You says.
In fact, Paniai hit a low point just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas carols by a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke through the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers was offended by her tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers, who had been drinking, chased and beat the group with their rifle butts, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired at the group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government commission building was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field outside the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird's song - of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military posts.
As the mood heated up, an order was sent to the soldiers via an internal radio: "If the masses resist more than three times, shoot them dead", says an official document from TIME that was not released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood of Enarotali, saw the imminent danger and called for calm and urged the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist", he told TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but he says the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, many shots were fired", he adds.
Local man Alfius Youw was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", said Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, has only one name, Time, in a gloomy mood.
"I saw he was dead... I kissed him".
Papua's chief police inspector, Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were only trying to "secure" her station because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us", said Papua Police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
For three weeks, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the historic grievances in Papua.
"I want this case solved immediately so it won't happen again", he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said he would establish an extrajudicial mechanism to address historical human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most of the injuries were long ago.
Some were in the '90s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but there are processes that need to be passed through", he said.
