But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been at large for decades, civil rights activists say the twin motivations behind the lynchings have always been known throughout the city: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in the summer primary.
About the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black tenant farmer Roger Malcolm stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight, allegedly over a woman.
Brooks said the rumor in town was that Hester slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and that the baby she was carrying wasn't her husband's.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to free Malcolm from prison, according to the FBI.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But then as they were leaving the prison and approaching Moore's Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
