New results of Swedish Asylum Age Assessment tests published
Recent results from tests on asylum seekers in Sweden who have been subjected to a new medical method for assessing their age show that more than 80 percent of those tested are over 18 years old.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started conducting the tests last year.
They are intended to improve the accuracy of age assessment during asylum procedures, following criticism of the Swedish Migration Authority (Migrationsverket) for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed the person as "possibly 18 or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "possibly under 18 years of age".
The tests are only performed in cases where the age of the person is in question.
According to Johan Göransson from the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see a big difference in the statistics from the past few months, the numbers are pretty consistent", he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases where the person was assessed as over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his or her age.
In May, the agency released results from 581 tests and said there were 442 cases that "suggested the person being tested was 18 years or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that he would be 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI images of knee joints, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some quarters.
One skeptic is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of humans to see if they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think that kind of measurement should be used.
Assessing biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say it for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told Metro.
Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, however, defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is low.
The greatest risk is when the person is just under 18, in which case it is about 10 percent".
