NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be given access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September following a High Court battle over funding for the drug on the NHS.
NHS England announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken before sexual intercourse, which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 percent, is now being provided by the NHS through an initial three-year study involving an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to finance the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS had the authority to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was hailed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as an "important new intervention", while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called it a "decisive moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, with more clinics to follow in October before rolling out across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a sequence of HIV medicines taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that just enough medication is in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day or so, two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will identify suitable participants who agree to the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People living in England and registered with a GP can also register for potential participation at their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The study aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is used, taken up and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and outpace the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of mankind's greatest health challenges".
Deborah Gold, chief executive of NAT, said: "This is a critical moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at vulnerable and disadvantaged people, has the potential to change the UK HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individual controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, which will lead to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement".
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now has to be to get the trial done quickly across the country and not leave anyone at risk of HIV behind.
Now that the PrEP trial drug is available, we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people with HIV".
Sharon Hodgson, Shadow Health Secretary, said: "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and reluctance by the government to implement.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and stopping the transmission of this life-altering infection.
This trial brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that this study is carried out nationwide as soon as possible to protect people living with HIV and that it helps us get one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society.'
