They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal inside the 2,500-pound [1,100 kg] lump of earth.
After all this hard work, the finished product is now ready to be revealed.
"If you blink a little, you could almost believe it was asleep", said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
"It will go down in the annals of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs".
Researchers have found that this herbivore, although covered in armor and resembling a walking tank, was likely threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used a red and white cloak to hide from predators, and used a shielding technique known as counter shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend in better with its environment and avoid its enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the Nodosaurus family made headlines for the first time in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal, naming it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor on its body.
They discovered the counter shading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, which means the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although the counter-scattering is common, the results are surprising, since the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of the animals alive today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was hunted by enough pressure from carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favored the concealment of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most modern animals that use countershading -- think deer, zebras, or belts -- are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, which signals that this nodosaur was in a real fight for survival.
"Strong predator behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous must have been", Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to examine the animal for clues to its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was swept out to sea, where it sank to the bottom of the sea on its back.
