How an activist came to know the answer to the question, "Whose Streets?"
On August 9th, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just one day after arriving in New York City, the St. Louis native was sitting on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolling through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone from high school.
"Police just killed an 18-year-old kid, and he's still lying in the street", it said.
Confused that no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis area rapper was about to tweet live the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street, and it would stay there for four hours.
"This is crazy", Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She hung up her phone to return to tweets about people on the Canfield drive later that evening.
There were photos of the police band and people screaming and a man claiming to be Brown's father carrying a sign that said, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
She was watching a live feed of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another officer unloaded his rifle and shouted, "I'm gonna kill you... animals all".
"That's not common", Ferrell recalled her statement.
"This is not the kind of murder we're used to, and we can call it typical".
At that moment, I felt a chill.
I was angry and I cried".
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two of them would head to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", in theaters starting October 11.
It's a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience, told from the perspective of people who live in the community and filled the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and a matching crown, the two discussed a conversation they had had countless times before that morning about the black experience and the black condition.
"Remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she remembered what she said.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn't right.
I couldn't take her", Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a culmination of what happened in the past.
She needs to know it and see it and be raised in it.
It has to be well developed, not only activism and organization, but also knowing the different layers of black experience and black constitution and what we have to do to become free, to free ourselves.
Even though I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she personally doesn't experience blatant racism, she's no different than the next black woman's child.
I feel I'd be doing her a disservice if I kept her away from it".
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place across from the police station that became a campground while activists waited for the possible non-indictment of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who was making lunch.
They prepared bags and helped to distribute them to protesters.
Slowly, a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism has changed completely since August 9", she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food equity and health inequities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come through".
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what happened.
A question popped into Ferrell's head: "Do you want to document or are you trying to find a story you can exploit?"
This skepticism has been fueled by countless cases of people, often white, in a community that has benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We had heard that people who were born and raised in Ferguson didn't have their voices centered, and we wanted to do something different".
Folayan had previously worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism around death row inmates.
His commitment brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals who followed the team of Whose Streets? in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks to us.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that's how I'm going to be portrayed".
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement is "not about a messiah leader, but a community coming together", Folayan said - she proved to be the most outspoken participant in the film.
As a result, documents from Whose Streets? show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life as she falls in love and marries her wife.
"I felt naked", said Ferrell, laughing as she saw the finished product for the first time.
"But I've learned that in this work, in humanizing black people, there has to be a certain vulnerability".
Furthermore, Ferrell's story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement who influenced the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in the social media movie "BlacklivesMatter" identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement as a whole", Ferrell said, "and so we're constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of everything".
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really being sustained by black women and many black women".
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action" in which Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up that energy", she said.
"It's no coincidence that she was at the front lines, "because a life at these crossroads as a black, gay woman is so much at stake.
You can feel their energy through the screen".
Now, the news cameras in Ferguson are long gone, but the racial ties between the community and the police continue.
Ferrell is on probation for two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls home as "a mess".
Yet she clings to a song and feels committed to that memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We must love and support one another.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains".
