A fitting analogy: an artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning 's DNA .
In the center of the room at the Fridman Gallery in New York, you can see many faces - white, black and brown, almost imperceptibly similar - hanging from cables in the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek puppets and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clips from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic messages through the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman and groundbreaking dissident whose conviction was overturned by Barack Obama when he was just three days into office.
Dewey-Hagborg, by algorithmically analyzing the DNA that Manning extracted and creating 30 portraits of what someone with this genomic data might look like, has created a sharp, if somewhat intellectual, commentary not only on the formability of DNA data -- the many ways it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations -- but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has been open about identifying as a woman since her adolescence, was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her image was suppressed by the prison, so much so that there was only one photo -- a grainy, black and white selfie of Manning visibly uncomfortable in a driver's seat wearing a platinum blonde wig -- that she was associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was just coming off the huge success of her 2012 project Stranger Visions.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts like cigarette butts and gum by extracting DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That's when she got an email from a newspaper magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted a kind of portrait to accompany this article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't be visited at the time and she couldn't be photographed, so you contacted Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to do a DNA profile.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unequal correspondents, exchanging several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic strip, "Suppressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which predicted a future where President Chelsea would change her mind and she would be able to see the exhibit in person.
The fact that Obama would actually demand Manning's release just days after the book was published after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas was a welcome kind of happy reunion.
There's something profound and powerful about the opening of the exhibition as Donald Trump wages a war against government informants and against transgender troops to find new, tweety ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to be fixing.
When Dewey-Hagborg was asked about the strange timing of all these things, she said that "Things happen for a reason".
In an artistic statement written on the gallery wall, Manning, with her oversized signature below (the "i" in her family name is a heart), called for an end to the "automatic fragmentation based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite wall is their mitochondrial DNA sequence -- a thousandth of Cs and Gs and As, written in pencil.
Dewey-Hagborg hoped that by including the 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's highly developed scientific lexicon) she could show how amazingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"What people will hopefully take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open to interpretation genetic data is and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work Spurious Memories is also on view.
"DNA data can tell so many different stories, so that's 30 of those stories".
The last piece in the exhibition, which is kept in a separate room, is a page from the aforementioned comic novel.
She shows Manning emerging from the United States' disciplinary cells like King Kong with a pay phone in her hand.
"If they don't hear you, they've won".
"So never shut up".
"It came straight from a letter she wrote me", said the artist, who greets from Philadelphia.
"I still get goose bumps when I talk about it".
Manning has not yet seen the exhibit in person, as predicted in the comic book, but if she does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room by the masks, by her own genomic simulators, swarming like hordes of protesters.
This was also targeted, like everything in the exhibit, right down to the size (5" 2, Manning's stature) where their genetic haplogroups were written in pencil.
"In the past I had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that formed with Chelsea, like the movement that was behind her liberation".
