The PM commented on the second part of WADA's Code Compliance Roadmap, which outlines the criteria for the reinstatement of RUSADA and was recently published on the organisation's website.
Mutko says it contains nothing that could cause Russia to worry.
"Everything has been announced, everything is being implemented.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future", he added.
However, one of the criteria listed states that the Russian anti-doping authorities must publicly accept the reported results of the WADA-approved investigation by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren into alleged state-sponsored doping in Russian sport.
In this regard, Mutko said: "We are conducting the investigation because our anti-doping system has admitted a mistake.
All measures have been implemented.
But there were no government programs, and we will not admit to something that does not exist".
Mutko's words were in line with those of Vitaly Smirnov, the head of Russia's independent anti-doping commission.
Speaking to Russian outlet RSport earlier in the day, Smirnov admitted past problems in Russian anti-doping organizations, but added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one intends to accept this report unconditionally", Smirnov added.
In November 2015, following the doping scandal, RUSADA was banned by WADA from conducting doping controls in Russia.
However, it was allowed to plan and coordinate tests under the supervision of international experts and the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
After visiting the organization's headquarters in Moscow in July, WADA Director-General Olivier Niggli stated that RUSADA was "moving in the right direction" to be reinstated.
