The startups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure your employees' happiness at your e-commerce startup, but the polls didn't work.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful, or, worse, misleading.
And even if you promised anonymity, some workers didn't trust the process.
"There was just never consistency and objectivity", said Errett, who runs the 75-person San Francisco e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed.
She called in outside help.
A new breed of human resource start-ups is growing to help companies figure out how their employees feel.
By building and licensing software that has the specific purpose of measuring employee engagement, it enables companies to conduct surveys, target specific groups and demographics, provide employees with anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass C-suite executives and contact the board directly.
"You now have tools like Strava and Fitbit to track your health, but where's the Fitbit for your business?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and chief executive of Redwood City startup Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she gained a better insight into what your employees think and feel in the three years with Glint.
In addition to Snap surveys and surveys of specific teams, it provides a company heat map that shows at a glance which units have the most complaints and which executives have low approval scores - so you can dig into why.
Companies are coming to realize that they need to stay on top of workplace culture so they don't become the next Uber to be embroiled in scandal, ever since a former employee posted a blog post describing an environment of harassment where those who spoke up were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire for a complete overview is a lucrative business opportunity.
The global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020, according to financial technology website Let's Talk Payments.
Denver, Colorado, startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a surge in interest and activity earlier this year amid the Uber case in bad credit.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send customized pulse surveys, collect confidential real-time answers, and view heat maps of your problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous texting hotline for employees to report misconduct.
