"I find it so beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years", he says wistfully.
"What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand".
'A Castle in England' spans the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era, documenting the families that lived in Scotney, each story illustrated by a different emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It's not Rhodes' first book to be based on an archive: he wrote Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
"I was just reacting to the thumbprint on the page of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins", he says.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because back then, people would light fires for the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has the effect of being there.
I love archives, you know?"
For someone who is so battered with old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England and lived in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I overestimated my welcome greeting a little bit") all this seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, sifting through the archives, and studying the castle's many treasures and curiosities, such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and the bottles that had been in the ditch for centuries.
He wandered through the grounds and ruins of the old castle and talked with landscapers, gardeners, and sometimes even with the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he drank "whiskey and started writing".
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain full access until 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the staff had just begun to take care of the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years in which aristocrats said, 'Oh, throw it in the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You might think land disputes would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a birch tree that the two families fought over.
Guys, let it go!"
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve into English history on a broader basis, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that took place in the castle in 1380, in this book entitled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex'", says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising started in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle's history - like 'The Priest', which tells the story of the Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler,' which depicts 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with rocks (a discovery made only years later when his coffin was excavated).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favourite Scotney family: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite the crooks, going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking guys with a talent for soliciting heirs".
After his time at the castle is over, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness writing a comic novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th-century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave again", he says.
