Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may help relieve inflammatory bowel disease
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare to your digestive system.
But a new study suggests just the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could alleviate the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, which affects about 1.3 million in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While sufferers are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan from proteins helps to develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not enter the body.
Cells that are capable of causing inflammation are replaced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
If the balance is too much in the direction of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can result.
In experiments, a type of tolerance-promoting immune cell was found in mice that carried a particular bacterium in their intestines.
And the bacteria needs tryptophan -- one of the building blocks of proteins -- to make the cells look like they are.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the gut microbiome and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet promotes a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment, if the same system works in humans.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan was studying a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had these cells, but another group of the same strain, but housed separately, did not.
She speculated that the difference had to do with the gut microbiome of the mice -- the community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The gut DNA of the mice was sequenced, and they found six species of bacteria that were present in the mice with the immune cells, but missing in the mice without them.
So mice were raised in a sterile environment, so they lacked a gut microbiome, and they didn't develop these types of immune cells, and they got L. reuteri, and the immune cells developed.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells evolved into the tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active ingredient was removed from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when they halved the tryptophan levels, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop cells in humans as they do in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said, "The development of these cells is probably something we want to encourage, because these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the gut.
Potentially, high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri may lead to an expansion of this population.'
