Interview: "Domsparzen report clears Pope-brother Georg Ratzinger of his guilt"
The Regensburg Domsparzen report on the abuse cases exonerates Pope Brother Georg Ratzinger.
That is what author and historian Michael Hesemann says.
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg Domspatzen is still provoking discussion.
Christian Weisnder, a spokesman for the reform movement We Are Church, told the German Press Agency after the publication that he expects an apology from the former bishop of Regensburg and current Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller and from the cathedral chaplain Georg Ratzinger, the 93-year-old brother of retired Pope Benedict XVI.
It would be a great asset to the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret for their own failures or their then-false assessment of events.
The Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano", on the other hand, criticized the "double standard" in reporting violence among the cathedral sparrows.
Regarding the Regensburg attacks, no one doubts that they are "disgraceful and shameful acts" that should be punished and prevented in the future, but what is striking is the "degree of media manipulation", says author Lucetta Scaraffia, a historian and member of the Italian National Bioethics Committee.
"The habit of calling the Catholic Church the source of all evil is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to accept it as normal", Scaraffia writes.
Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis also said in an interview with the Bavarian Radio: "You like going to church and that's a found food".
She also noted that in her youth "beating was a normal educational tool" "to deal with naughty children like myself".
She felt it was unfair to apply today's standards to earlier decades, because the world had changed.
In connection with the reports of the abuse cases, the Pope's brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared.
Quite wrong, says author and historian Michael Hesemann, who wrote with Ratzinger the memoir "My Brother the Pope" (translated into 12 languages).
"I have to protect Georg Ratzinger", says Hesemann, "because none of this had anything to do with him", he evaluates the results of the final report.
What exactly is in the 440-page report submitted by the lawyer Ulrich Weber, who was commissioned by the Diocese of Regensburg to investigate?
A total of 547 Regensburg Cathedral sparrows were victims of sexual abuse between 1945 and the early 1990s, 67 of them with a high degree of plausibility.
The final report says of Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994: "In summary, then, it can be said that in many cases, forms of physical and psychological violence were used by the cathedral chaplain R.
Especially when the students were highly emotional, the punishment for them could be more severe.
Nevertheless, it is striking that, unlike many other defendants, many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore, in many cases, even in spite of the violence, associate positive memories with him".
In the interview, Hesemann explains why he believes the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg Domspatzen relieves Georg Ratzinger of his responsibility.
Mr Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "Incidents of violence against those under protection among the Regensburg Cathedral sparrows" gives a contradictory picture of the cathedral chaplain Georg Ratzinger.
For one thing, many students highlight his "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist who often became a handyman when a cathedral sparrow did not perform musically.
As his biographer, what do you think of this final report?
Michael Hesemann: If you go through the entire 440-page report from front to back, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger even appears in it.
It is only eight pages long and it clearly absolves him of any suspicion of complicity or knowledge in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The violence at the preschool also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
At best, he may be accused of being too late to learn or of not taking the first hints seriously enough.
The cathedral grammar school where he worked was perceived by virtually all respondents as - quite literally - "salvation", "heaven", and "a better world".
So too, the vast majority of Georg Ratzinger's students give a very fine testimony, describing him as "warmhearted", "lovely", "sincere", "competent", and "compassionate", as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, cookies, and candy, and who was "always overwhelmed with grapes from children".
Only a minority complain of his perfectionism and high emotionality, which have led to angry outbursts.
He admitted years ago that he not only banged chairs and threw the key chain on the floor, but also slapped and pulled too many naughty boys by the hair or ears. He deeply regretted it and apologized.
To his credit, however, such parenting methods were widespread in the 1960's and 1970's, among parents and teachers alike.
Do you know of any other methods of punishment?
Of course, I think any of us born before 1968.
I too experienced this in a secular school, a state high school.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, and I am sure that the Commission will be able to do so.
You wonder if it's not more to do with his fame and his role as Benedict XVI's brother that many media outlets are now jumping on him.
The Bavarian Pope is still being worked on by many who have never understood him.
The truth is that the report absolves Georg Ratzinger in every respect.
The report has been widely reported in the media on the subject of abuse among the Regensburg sparrows.
Does the final report also charge Georg Ratzinger with any involvement or knowledge of sexual abuse?
Michael Hesemann: Obviously not.
None of the 67 victims of sexual assault claim to have confided in the cathedral chaplain.
Even the parents weren't informed.
"I never dared to talk to my father or mother about it", one sufferer said on behalf of the others, "it was all very embarrassing".
The real problem with educating about sexual abuse was, and is, that most victims are silent out of shame.
If they did not confide in their parents and siblings, they certainly did not confide in a choir director who was a colleague of the perpetrators.
How do the Domspatzen students rate Ratzinger's role in the abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: One student interviewed put it this way: "As for sexual abuse . . . I don't see . . . any case where he [Georg Ratzinger] alone had timely information and could have stopped the perpetrator.
I think it's... it's really absurd to think that boys open up to him more than their parents, boarding school administrators, trusted teachers, etc.
Talking to him about sex is unthinkable".
The report concludes that 'the fact that the pupils and/or their environment concerned confided in advance to him could not be confirmed in the investigation'.
So as far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger must be cleared of any involvement.
It is not possible to accuse him of not having prevented or brought him to justice.
There is no reason to associate his good name with these heinous crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
The media have reported extensively on "excesses of violence" among the Regensburg Cathedral Sparrows.
The former chaplain of the cathedral, Georg Ratzinger, is accused of "looking the other way" in the report.
Does he have to live with that?
Michael Hesemann: That's the big problem, that in the coverage, everything was mixed and matched into a huge mix of sexual abuse and violence and somewhere in the middle, Georg Ratzinger.
But that is exactly what is wrong with the report.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, and I am sure that the Commission will be able to do so.
The report also covers incidents since 1945, including four decades during which Georg Ratzinger was not choirmaster.
The whole terrible school-based beatings, the cases where boys were being bullied and abused by sadistic teachers and suffered horribly, all took place in the kindergartens in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where really scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But Georg Ratzinger, the chaplain of the cathedral, had nothing to do with them, for he did not see the boys until they were already in the cathedral grammar school.
At that time, as most witnesses point out, the subject of "preschool" was taboo.
One was just happy to escape it and enjoyed the much better treatment and, for many, even "paradiselike" conditions.
What was different about the Cathedral Sparrow School?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but there was no sadistic violence.
And so did Georg Ratzinger, who concluded that "many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore, in many cases, even in spite of the violence, associate positive memories with him".
At best, it's a charge of looking the other way.
But despite all efforts, the report could only identify two periods in which he was informed of conditions at the preschool.
The first time was in 1970/71, when he was just starting out and did not want to hear about the school he was not involved in and was in charge of, and then again in about 1993.
Georg Ratzinger consistently shut his ears to the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because back in 1989, he wrote a letter to the principal of the Cathedral Sparrow School, which the report even reproduces.
In it he warns them "that the practice of spanking in preschools will continue".
The Commission has already taken a number of measures to combat the problem of the use of the euro.
This was, of course, at a time when there was legal clarity, when beatings were long since banned in Bavaria.
Before that, they were in a legal gray area, as we all know.
It was also difficult for him to assess where the persons concerned might have exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he was always looking away.
That's just not true.
It was not until 1980 that the punishment of school beatings was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis argued that it was unfair to apply today's educational standards to the times.
How do you see it?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the "trap of anachronism", the danger of judging the past by today's moral standards.
The princess is right.
But this is not true of sexual abuse, which has always been abhorrent, nor of the acts of violence and cruelty committed against innocent children in preschool, which go far beyond what was common then.
This is all very terrible and I'm glad it's finally being worked out.
But at the same time, I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because none of this had anything to do with him.
His means of discipline and punishment, spanking and pulling at the hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When corporal punishment was then prohibited, he also strictly adhered to it.
What picture of his Regensburg days did Georg Ratzinger reproduce in his conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Did the subject of beatings come up?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, who is Pope Benedict XVI, told from his perspective, and the sparrows played a minor role.
I'm not hiding the fact that he was a strict regiment.
But it must be said that without this perfectionism, without the demand for unconditional discipline, it would have been hardly possible for him to transform the hitherto more nationally known Regensburg Domspatzen into a world-class institution, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, who toured twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With cookies and candy alone, you can't make a rebellious boy into a great singer and you can't beat success in any field, but always discipline, passion and self-control.
What kind of person did you see Georg Ratzinger as during the discussions about your book?
Michael Hesemann: Working on the book and beyond, I really got to know Georg Ratzinger very well and I experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, fundamental, deeply religious, kindhearted man who you can't imagine would hurt even a fly.
I regularly hear how many former parish priests, 23 years after his retirement, still keep in regular contact with him, visit him, read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him as a member of their family.
So those who still do not forgive him for being harsh with them are clearly in the minority.
Most of the Cathedral sparrows are grateful to him today for enriching their lives and bringing them closer to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher -- a strict father, sure, but also a loving, respectful person that they still look up to and actually adore.
And again, please, be very clear: all that is being accused of is parenting methods that were on the agenda at the time.
We can be glad we've moved past that time.
But it's highly unfair to make a man, just because he's prominent and has an even more prominent brother, the media scapegoat.
The evil intent behind it is all too obvious.
Because the report that just came out cleared him.
Now decency would command a 93-year-old man who has earned great merits and without whom no one outside Bavaria and perhaps even Germany would know the Regensburg Domspatzen, to finally leave him alone.
